9 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
10 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 23 O.S. 2021, Section 61.2, is
11 amended to read as follows:
12 Section 61.2. A. In any civil action arising from a claimed
13 bodily injury, the amount of compensation which the trier of fact
14 may award a plaintiff for economic loss shall not be subject to any
15 limitation.
16 B. Except as provided in subsection C of this section, in any
17 civil action arising from a claimed bodily injury, the amount of
18 compensation which a trier of fact may award a plaintiff for
19 noneconomic loss shall not exceed Three Hundred Fifty Thousand
20 Dollars ($350,000.00) Five Hundred Thousand Dollars ($500,000.00),
21 regardless of the number of parties against whom the action is
22 brought or the number of actions brought.
23 C. Notwithstanding subsection B of this section, there shall be
24 no limit on the amount of noneconomic damages which the trier of
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1065 Page 1

1 fact may award the plaintiff in a civil action arising from a
2 claimed bodily injury resulting from negligence if the judge and
3 jury finds, by clear and convincing evidence, that the defendant’s
4 acts or failures to act were:
5 1. In reckless disregard for the rights of others;
6 2. Grossly negligent;
7 3. Fraudulent; or
8 4. Intentional or with malice.
9 D. In the trial of a civil action arising from claimed bodily
10 injury, if the verdict is for the plaintiff, the court, in a nonjury
11 trial, shall make findings of fact, and the jury, in a trial by
12 jury, shall return a general verdict accompanied by answers to
13 interrogatories, which shall specify all of the following:
14 1. The total compensatory damages recoverable by the plaintiff;
15 2. That portion of the total compensatory damages representing
16 the plaintiff’s economic loss;
17 3. That portion of the total compensatory damages representing
18 the plaintiff’s noneconomic loss; and
19 4. If alleged, whether the conduct of the defendant was or
20 amounted to:
21 a. reckless disregard for the rights of others,
22 b. gross negligence,
23 c. fraud, or
24 d. intentional or malicious conduct.
