1 E. In any civil action to recover damages arising from claimed
2 bodily injury, after the trier of fact makes the findings required
3 by subsection D of this section, the court shall enter judgment in
4 favor of the plaintiff for economic damages in the amount determined
5 pursuant to paragraph 2 of subsection D of this section, and subject
6 to paragraph 4 of subsection D of this section, the court shall
7 enter a judgment in favor of the plaintiff for noneconomic damages.
8 Except as provided in subsection C of this section, in no event
9 shall a judgment for noneconomic damages exceed the maximum
10 recoverable amounts set forth in subsection B of this section.
11 Subsection B of this section shall be applied in a jury trial only
12 after the trier of fact has made its factual findings and
13 determinations as to the amount of the plaintiff’s damages.
14 F. In any civil action arising from claimed bodily injury which
15 is tried to a jury, the jury shall not be instructed with respect to
16 the limit on noneconomic damages set forth in subsection B of this
17 section, nor shall counsel for any party nor any witness inform the
18 jury or potential jurors of such limitations.
19 G. This section shall not apply to actions brought under The
20 Governmental Tort Claims Act or actions for wrongful death brought
21 pursuant to Section 7 of Article XXIII of the Oklahoma Constitution.
22 H. As used in this section:
23 1. “Bodily injury” means actual physical injury to the body of
24 a person and sickness or disease resulting therefrom;
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1065 Page 3

1 2. “Economic damages” means any type of pecuniary harm
2 including, but not limited to:
3 a. all wages, salaries or other compensation lost as a
4 result of a bodily injury that is the subject of a
5 civil action,
6 b. all costs incurred for medical care or treatment,
7 rehabilitation services, or other care, treatment,
8 services, products or accommodations as a result of a
9 bodily injury that is the subject of a civil action,
10 or
11 c. any other costs incurred as a result of a bodily
12 injury that is the subject of a civil action;
13 3. “Fraudulent” or “fraud” means “actual fraud” as defined
14 pursuant to Section 58 of Title 15 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
15 4. “Gross negligence” means the want of slight care and
16 diligence;
17 5. “Malice” involves hatred, spite or ill will, or the doing of
18 a wrongful act intentionally without just cause or excuse;
19 6. “Noneconomic damages” means nonpecuniary harm that arises
20 from a bodily injury that is the subject of a civil action,
21 including damages for pain and suffering, loss of society,
22 consortium, companionship, care, assistance, attention, protection,
23 advice, guidance, counsel, instruction, training, education,
24 disfigurement, mental anguish and any other intangible loss; and
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1065 Page 4

1 7. “Reckless disregard of another’s rights” shall have the same
2 meaning as willful and wanton conduct and shall mean that the
3 defendant was either aware, or did not care, that there was a
4 substantial and unnecessary risk that his, her or its conduct would
5 cause serious injury to others. In order for the conduct to be in
6 reckless disregard of another’s rights, it must have been
7 unreasonable under the circumstances and there must have been a high
8 probability that the conduct would cause serious harm to another
9 person.
10 I. This section shall apply to civil actions filed on or after
11 November 1, 2011 November 1, 2025.
12 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
